    "image": "https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-020/1200/700",
    "excerpt": "For hydration habits that actually stick, I compared my old all-or-nothing method with a smaller repeatable system. The second approach looked less intense on paper but performed better in real life.",
    "content": "<p>The old method aimed for perfect days and failed hard when schedules shifted. The new method aimed for continuity and could survive interruptions at places like the living room floor mat.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-127/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 20 image 1\"><p>Old pattern: react late, improvise, and get trapped by adding extra sets late at night. Each day created fresh decisions, so cognitive load kept increasing.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-128/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 20 image 2\"><p>New pattern: pairing hydration with the first movement cue, then starting with low-intensity movement, and finish by resetting a small notebook. I ran this sequence in short blocks and treated completion quality as secondary to consistency.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-129/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 20 image 3\"><p>After 9 weeks, the contrast was clear. Resting heart rate improved around 44 percent, and sleep onset time improved around 9 percent without heavy rebound.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-130/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 20 image 4\"><p>The lesson was simple: stable rhythm beats heroic bursts. When setbacks happened, a 19-minute fallback protected momentum, and baseline performance usually recovered inside 46 hours. Keeping a marked bottle at each work zone made intake visible and prevented long gaps during busy afternoons.</p>"
