    "image": "https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-031/1200/700",
    "excerpt": "While improving a closet layout that cuts decision fatigue, I kept running into advice that sounded smart but failed in practice. Breaking those myths into concrete tests made the routine lighter and more dependable.",
    "content": "<p>I kept a small myth card at the office elevator lobby and checked it weekly. That simple habit prevented me from repeating the same expensive mistakes.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-171/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 31 image 1\"><p>Myth one: more effort always means better results. Reality: once treating limited discounts as urgent needs appears, effort alone usually amplifies noise. Countermove: start with checking care labels before every wash and protect the baseline first.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-172/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 31 image 2\"><p>Myth two: more metrics always improve control. In practice, tracking only commute comfort score and monthly wear count per item gave cleaner decisions. By week 9, those two indicators were enough to guide changes.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-173/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 31 image 3\"><p>Myth three: every mistake must be fixed the same day. My data showed the opposite. When washing delicate fabrics on autopilot happened, a 25-minute fallback prevented deeper drift and made next-day recovery faster.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-174/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 31 image 4\"><p>Once the myths were removed, execution became quieter and far less emotional. That shift is what finally unlocked mornings started with less rushing in a sustainable way.</p>"
