    "image": "https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-046/1200/700",
    "excerpt": "I documented flexible city-day plans that still feel structured as a weekly logbook focused on actions, friction points, and outcomes. By week 10, the most valuable piece was not intensity but a reliable rollback path.",
    "content": "<p>Week one note: at the city metro exit, I got stalled by ignoring energy dips in the afternoon on three different days. The hardest part was not physical effort; it was the repeated cost of rebuilding decisions.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-231/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 46 image 1\"><p>Weeks two to four: I changed the entry step to limiting each day to one primary activity and reset a luggage scale immediately after each block. That small change improved startup speed by about 7 percent.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-232/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 46 image 2\"><p>From week five onward, I froze extra variables and watched only overweight luggage count and transfer time between stops. Narrow metrics made debugging faster when performance dipped.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-233/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 46 image 3\"><p>One notable setback happened at the station transfer corridor when stacking too many hard deadlines in one day crept back in and added 28 minutes. Instead of forcing a full catch-up, I ran two fallback sessions to restore continuity first.</p><img src=\"https://picsum.photos/seed/luchu-234/1200/700\" style=\"width: 100%; border-radius: 20px; margin: 30px 0;\" alt=\"Article 46 image 4\"><p>The logbook confirmed a useful rule: systems that survive bad days outperform systems that look perfect once in a while. With that rule, baseline usually returned within 55 hours and travel mood stayed steadier throughout the day stayed visible.</p>"
